post_text:
ALL STUDENTS ARE ELIGIBLE!
All Sherburne-Earlville Central School District students (UPK-12) are eligible to receive no-cost meals every day school is in session during the 2020-2021 academic year.

Blended and virtual-only students are entitled to one breakfast and one lunch per school day at no charge. The school will serve meals to blended students when they are on campus for in-person instruction. Pre-packaged meals will be available for both blended and virtual-only students to cover off-campus school days.

Parents/guardians must sign up to receive no-cost meals for virtual school days. Families with multiple SECSD students only need to complete one sign-up form. Please click on this link and fill out the form to sign up: https://forms.gle/84ddq8WdxVuYEJgK7.

This no-cost meals program is scheduled to begin September 14. Details regarding the distribution process of no-cost meals on virtual school days is forthcoming.
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #SchoolsReopening #NoCostMeals2020

K-5 VIRTUAL STUDENTS: Get your device today!
Virtual-only students in grades K-5 picked up school-issued devices and met with their teachers Thursday morning in the Sherburne-Earlville Elementary School gymnasium.

If your family couldn’t make it this morning, an afternoon device pick-up session will run from 1-3 p.m. today in the same place.

Again, today’s device pick-up sessions are for SEES students (K-5) who have chosen our Virtual Learning platform to start the 2020-2021 school year.

For more information on our School Reopening, visit https://www.secsd.org/SchoolReopening2020-2021.aspx online.

post_text:
ELEMENTARY NEWS

Letters with teachers and cohort assignments are being mailed. The high number of requested changes has delayed finalization of lists. We know that you need this information to plan, and we appreciate your patience in this process. If you need this information before you receive the mailing, you can call 607-674-7336 on Saturday, August 29th from 9:00 am to 12:00 pm or on Monday, August 31st from 8:00 am to 3:00 pm or email Ms. Halliday at hallidaya@seonline.org. Students in the Sherburne - Earlville Virtual Academy (SEVA) can pick up their devices and meet their teachers from 9-11 or 1-3 on September 3rd. UPK and K students can also visit their classrooms on September 3rd. Times for these visits will be in the packet mailed to you. Again, thank you for your patience!

Sherburne Earlville PTO
July 25 at 9:07 AM ·

Lifetouch has sent another notification that the elementary yearbooks are still delayed due to continued Covid-19 closures and positive cases in their plants. At this time I don’t have a confirmed ship date . As soon as I have more information I will post details on when and where the yearbooks will be available for pickup. I know this is disappointing news, thank you for your continued patience and understanding.

FALL SPORTS WILL BE DELAYED
Officers of the New York State Public High School Athletic Association voted Thursday to delay the start of the 2020 Fall Sports season until September 21.

Should the COVID-19 health crisis further disrupt the 2020 Fall Sports season, the NYSPHSAA will implement short-season schedules for all high school sports starting in January 2021.

Click the NYSPHSAA link below to read more about the future of high school sports in New York.
#WeAreSE #SEStrong #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #FallSports2020

post_text:
Calling all S-E parents - we need your input! We understand it is challenging to plan your transportation when we are not sure what school will look like. That being said, with restrictions on how many students we can seat, we need to have the best (tentative) data possible in order to plan our opening.

Please complete both the technology survey and the transportation survey below. It should not take more than 5 minutes.

Technology Needs Survey: https://forms.gle/6W86QcL2dc6d7mg18
Transportation Needs Survey:
https://forms.gle/Xs1bfMni4ygcNo8k8

If we can get 500 responses by Friday, July 17th, the admin team will put out their very own TikTok! 🤣 (300 responses so far - keep it up!)

Thank you!

#WeAreSE

Those who pre-ordered 2020 Sherburne-Earlville Middle School Yearbooks but have yet to pick them up should call Penny Gager in the SEMS Office at 607-674-7350.

SECTION 3 TO HONOR S-E SENIOR!
Congratulations to Sherburne-Earlville senior Makayla Cornelius, who will be honored as a Section 3 Scholar-Athlete later this month!

Makayla is a three-sport varsity athlete (soccer, softball, volleyball) who ranks third overall in academics at Sherburne-Earlville. She plans to enter the nursing program at Onondaga Community College this fall.

Section 3 typically honors its Scholar-Athletes with an Awards Night Dinner at Onondaga CC’s SRC Arena. Since this is not possible in 2020 because of the COVID-19 pandemic, Makayla and the rest of Section 3’s Scholar-Athletes will be honored with a slide-show presentation at 6 p.m. June 15.

The Awards Show will air on CNY Central Channel 6 in Syracuse and the website https://cnycentral.com/.

Way to go, Makayla!
#WeAreSE #SEStrong #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #Section3ScholarAthlete2020
The Sherburne News LLC The Evening Sun CNYCentral.com CNY News thedailystar.com Section 3 Athletics Observer-Dispatch syracuse.com

PAGEANT OF BANDS: 2000s
~ 20 years ago (2000)
Laurens Central School won the Frank L. Miller Outstanding Director Award and Albert Whitney Overall Achievement Award at the 32nd Sherburne Pageant of Bands. North Syracuse was declared the JHS champion.

Held on June 1, 2 & 3 that year, this was the first pageant to feature bands from the Midwest as Roosevelt HS from Sioux Falls, South Dakota, and Sibley-Ocheyedan High School from Iowa made the long trek to Sherburne. Both bands were greeted by enthusiastic crowds at the parade!

~ Coming tomorrow: The 2010s

FOR YOUR HEALTH!
School-Based Health Centers near you are open, and you may be seen at any SBHC convenient to you.

Please call 844-255-7242 to schedule an in-person visit near you or to schedule a telemedicine visit. Remember, you can also easily communicate with your SBHC provider through MyBassett at https://www.mybassetthealthconnection.org.

The following SBHCs are open:
• Cooperstown
• Delhi
• Edmeston
• Laurens
• Middleburgh
• Morris
• Richfield Springs
• Sherburne
• Stamford
• Unadilla Valley
Other locations opening soon.

We have redesigned our protocols to provide safe and appropriate care! Call 844-ALL-SBHC (844-255-7242) Mon - Fri, 8 a.m. - 4 p.m.
Bassett Healthcare Network School-Based Health

I wanted to do something for my students for Memorial Day- since many places won't have bands and fireworks, I decided to make my own band. I hope this makes everyone feel festive today! (For anyone trying to make their own mashup, I definitely recommend using a metronome- I didn't because my headphones broke, but the videos need to quite literally line up to hundredths of a second. I did this on iMovie- glad the pandemic has allowed me to become more tech savvy!)

TOMORROW’S THE DAY!

On Wednesday, May 13th between the hours of 7:00 am and 7:00 pm, parents of elementary students can pick up belongings from the elementary gymnasium. You may enter the gym through one door and exit through the other. Please wear a face mask. If you don’t have one, we will provide one for you. Check out our lost and found while you are here. Please return all library books (and Raising a Reader bags for UPK) at this time. We will also collect UPK and K registration forms. Parents of middle school students can pick up the contents of their child’s gym locker at the same location.

GO GREEN ON THURSDAYS!
It’s Mental Health Month, so show your support by wearing green on Thursdays in May!

We would love to see everyone wearing green while participating in activities that foster positive mental health. So for the entire month of May, we invite all Sherburne-Earlville community members to share photos of themselves participating in activities that are good for your mental health!

Need some suggestions? Here are some tips for our Marauder Family to work on our mental health every day.
* Talk to a friend or family member
* Identify something you are grateful for daily
* Make time to laugh

text:
GO GREEN ON THURSDAYS!
It’s Mental Health Month, so show your support by wearing green on Thursdays in May!

We would love to see everyone wearing green while participating in activities that foster positive mental health. So for the entire month of May, we invite all Sherburne-Earlville community members to share photos of themselves participating in activities that are good for your mental health!

Need some suggestions? Here are some tips for our Marauder Family to work on our mental health every day.
* Talk to a friend or family member
* Identify something you are grateful for daily
* Make time to laugh
* Follow a consistent sleep schedule
* Exercise
* Practice daily meditation
* Enjoy your hobbies
* Listen to music
* Practice deep breathing

Remember to wear green on Thursdays and to share your pics with us in the comments section below all month long!
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #SEStrong #MaroonAndWhite #MentalHealthMonth2020

YOUR SBHC TEAM CAN HELP!
All patients and families enrolled in Sherburne-Earlville’s School-Based Health Center can still reach the SBHC team by calling 844-ALL-SBHC (844-255-7242) toll free from 8 a.m.-4 p.m. Monday-Friday.

The SBHC team can help by:
~ Answering questions about general health concerns, including COVID-19
~ Renewing prescriptions
~ Scheduling visits with our Mental Health clinicians using telemedicine (a computer, tablet or smart phone and internet connection required)
~ Schedule visits with our Nurse Practitioners and Physician’s Assistant using telemedicine technology (a computer, tablet or smart phone and internet connection required). We can care for patients with illnesses and follow up on ongoing conditions such as asthma, depression requiring medication and ADD/ADHD.
~ Completing request forms or letters

#WeAreSE #SEFamily #SEStrong #MaroonAndWhite #SBHC2020

MVP FOR TESSA!
Congratulations to Sherburne-Earlville standout junior guard Tessa Cole, selected as Center State Conference Division I MVP for the 2019-2020 girls #basketball season.

Tessa scored 491 points during her junior season (23.4 points per game) and hit the 1,000-point milestone overall. She also averaged 5.6 rebounds, 4.6 steals and 3.7 assists for the Marauders, making a Section 3-best 65 three-point field goals along the way.

Check out Tessa's Twitter #video below to see how she's staying sharp!

SPRING INTO LEARNING

Elementary students can find their weekly assignments on our elementary website or by checking the platform used for their class (Google Classroom for 3-5, Dojo or Seesaw for K-2). Elementary teachers participated in online collaborative work sessions last week to develop consistent grade level learning experiences for students. In addition to the core classes, special area teachers collaborated to develop our "Specials Cafe", highlighting one of our special areas each day: Music Monday, Tech Tuesday, Workout Wednesday, Art Therapy Thursday, and Fun Read Friday. If you have questions about individual assignments, please contact your child's teacher. If you need an iPad for your K-2 student, we will be contacting you early in the week to discuss how we can get them to you. Offline assignment packets will be available at the pedestrian shelter at parent pick-up, which will be converted into "Wolfie's Imagination Station". Thank you for your continued support and patience as we embark on this new journey!
https://www.secsd.org/WEEKLYASSIGNMENTS.aspx

post_text:
CUTTING-EDGE CLIPS!
Sherburne-Earlville’s Jonathan Ryan is hooked on helping others.

Jon has been using the district’s Glowforge laser-cutter machine to carve out plastic clips for protective facemasks worn by caregivers during the COVID-19 crisis.

“I have seen pictures of people’s ears rubbed raw from wearing these masks all day long,” said Jon, a computer whiz who works as a teaching assistant at S-E. “Facemask straps can be hooked to these clips behind the head, which takes the pressure off of the ears.”

Jon, who wrote a grant for the Glowforge machine in November, is working on his third sheet of clips right now. Each sheet yields 66 clips.

Jon said he will deliver facemask clips to Community Memorial Hospital in Hamilton in the near future and can make more by request. For more information, email him at ryanj@seonline.org.
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #HookedOnHelping2020

post_text:
SEMS SHINES AT STEM SHOWCASE
Sherburne-Earlville Middle School sent 17 students to the annual STEM Showcase event at Mohawk Valley Community College in early March.

Our kids put their windmills, mousetrap cars and ping-pong-ball launchers to the test against students from other local school districts. We took first and second places in the MS mousetrap competition and also had the top ping-pong-ball launcher.

SEMS students, who competed in the windmill and mousetrap categories for the first time, also learned what they need to do to be competitive in the renewable energy KidWind Challenge in the future.
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #STEM2020

Gov. Andrew Cuomo announced Friday that schools would remain closed until April 15, 2020, because of the Coronavirus pandemic, at which time the situation would be reassessed. Schools were initially supposed to be closed for two weeks (March 18-April 1) as per the governor's executive order issued on March 17. Schools will be expected to continue with their plans for child care, meals and distance learning, and the 180-day waiver will remain in effect.

S-E inducted 20 newcomers during a March 12 ceremony at the MS/HS Auditorium: Jennifer Adsit, Morgan Boldt, Maleah Britton, Tessa Cole, Abigail Fontaine, Lily French, Courtney Geier, Alexandra Kellogg, Zoe Kellogg, Kathleen Keyes, Justiss Kovack, Bailey Lagoe, Madyson McCarthy, Bailey Mizrahi, Dalaney Parker, Peter Peschel, Alison Smith, Jonah Smith, Justine Strauss and Madison VanAlthuis.

The Class of 2020 tripled Sherburne-Earlville’s NHS membership as it joined current members Jessie Buruato, Makayla Cornelius, Troy Fleming, John Maltzan, Piper Page, Elizabeth Peila, Cassidy Rusweiler, Layne Sulton, Laura Tenney and Jaci Wright.

SCHOOL-BASED HEALTH CENTER CAN HELP
Bassett’s School-Based Health Center is still here for Sherburne-Earlville students and families during this stressful and scary time.

Although the SBHC at S-E is closed, the neighboring SBHC at Unadilla Valley is open for physicals and non-respiratory illnesses.

Additionally, we can address your concerns and needs via phone. Just call 1-844-255-7242, leave a message with our operator and we’ll get back to you as soon as possible. We can refer you to providers (medical, dental, mental health, etc.) and address medication-refill requests over the phone.

If you have COVID-19 concerns, please call 607-547-5555 to speak with a Bassett RN.

Please remind children to frequently wash their hands and to not touch their faces.

We think about S-E students and families every day and we miss them already! We are happy to be part of this wonderful community and we WILL make it through these tough times together.
~ School-Based Health Center staff
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite

post_text:
Although not our words, this is how your BOE sees our district staff. Thank you hardly seems sufficient for what you have done in the last three days.
- Sherburne-Earlville Board of Education President Deb Kurtz
shared_text:
Ken Buck
March 18 at 9:47 AM ·

We gave educators almost no notice. We asked them to completely redesign what school looks like and in about 24 hours local administrators and teachers "Apollo 13'ed" the problem and fixed it. Kids learning, children being fed, needs being met in the midst of a global crisis.
No state agency did this, no so-called national experts on curriculum. The local educators fixed it in hours. HOURS.
In fact, existing state and federal policies actually created multiple roadblocks. Local schools figured out how to do it around those too. No complaining and no handwringing - just solutions and amazingly clever plans.
Remember that the next time someone tries to convince you that schools are better run by mandates from non-educators. Remember that the next time someone tells you that teachers have it easy or try to persuade you that educators are not among the smartest, most ingenious people in society. And please never say to me again, "Those who can't do anything else just go into teaching."
Get out of the way of a teacher and watch with amazement at what really happens.

post_text:
#WeAreSE

As our area prepares for possible extended school closures, we know there are a lot of questions and concerns. To alleviate some of these, please know the following:

S-E is making plans to have meals available each school day. If you can't come to pick them up, we will deliver. In addition, our backpack program is ready to send out groceries to all families who indicated a need.

Administrators, teachers, staff, and mental health professionals will all be available. Our staff members are going to do their best to ensure learning continues. We are confident in the ability of our students to practice everything from math to manners while at home.

There is no shame in asking for help. Whether you can't figure out an equation or are wondering how to contact your insurance company - please ask. If we don't know the answer, we'll help find someone who does.

Call, e-mail, or message us - we are in this TOGETHER.

BLOOD DRIVE, LISTENING SESSION SET
The Sherburne-Earlville Central School District will host an American Red Cross Blood Drive from 8:30 a.m.-2:30 p.m. on Wednesday, March 11. The blood drive will take place in the MS/HS Auditorium.

The same day, the Board of Education will welcome Delaware-Chenango-Madison-Otsego BOCES Superintendent Perry Dewey for a listening session workshop to assist SECSD in the search for its next school Superintendent. The SECSD Board of Education values the participation and opinions of the community and hopes that you can attend the listening session.

shared_text:
RA-Bel Farm
March 5 at 9:06 AM ·

Please come out to watch Sherburne Earlville HS Musical - ONCE UPON A MATTRESS (event page is Once Upon A Mattress) at the Sherburne-Earlville Central School District auditorium. These kids are fantastic! Their progress has been nothing short of amazing in the past week, and they should be so proud of themselves.

I have been working with them for the past week on costumes. I was terrified to have any part of this. I have never had any theater experience and my costume experience has been limited to making them for kids and dogs at Halloween. However, these kids have been so incredibly respectful, patient, and grateful, that I would definitely help with future productions. They have even fanned the love of performing, that had been ignited in our child, when she attends rehearsals with me. These really are some great kids!

SEHS STUDENTS EXPLORE CAREERS
Sherburne-Earlville students in grades 9-12 are taking advantage of the high school career destinations program, which allows them to take part in shadowing experiences.

Employers in the community are more than happy to have students visit to gain first-hand knowledge of their workplaces and careers offered. This program is open to all SEHS students, who can see their counselor or Mrs. Winton to arrange a shadowing experience in a field of their choice.

Thank you to all of the businesses and people who have taken time out of their busy days to work with our students in this capacity!

WELCOME FFA PROGRAMS!
The Sherburne-Earlville Central School District welcomed local school districts Tuesday for the New York FFA Association’s District 4 Speaking Event.

FFA members from nine districts gathered in the S-E Middle/High School cafeteria before visiting various classrooms to compete in this New York FFA District Leadership Career Development Event.

At stake were berths in Sub-State Career Development events on March 14. Those who advance to Sub-State competition also earn the opportunity to qualify for the New York State FFA Convention in May. State winners move on to national competition later in the year.

FFA programs from Afton, Delaware Academy, Otselic Valley, Oxford, Sherburne-Earlville, Sidney, Unadilla Valley, Walton and Windsor participated Tuesday.
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #FFA2020

post_text:
INTERNET SAFETY TAKES CENTER STAGE
The Sherburne-Earlville Central School District thanks Alexa Benincasa for discussing the importance of Internet Safety with our S-E Middle School students the morning of January 31.

Alexa is an Investigative Specialist for the New York State Division of Criminal Services. She delivered a powerful, engaging and informative presentation at the S-E Middle School/High School Auditorium, reminding our kids to think hard before sharing anything online.

The New York State Missing Persons Clearinghouse at DCJS offers free presentations designed to help children learn the fundamentals of online safety. The 40-minute presentations teach safe and responsible practices and encourage students to keep their parents and teachers informed about what they are doing online. This includes all forms of social media, such as Snapchat, Instagram, Twitter and Facebook.

For more information, email the NYS Missing Persons Clearinghouse at missingpersons@dcjs.ny.gov or call 1-800-346-3543 (Option 1).
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #InternetSafety2020

post_text:
SPEAKING THE TRUTH
Thanks to Sergeant Smietana from the Chenango County Sheriff’s Office for taking the time to visit Jonathan Sherry's Civics class last week.

His conversation with the students was engaging and compelling on many levels. Most notably, he shared with the students that “Truth is the greatest justice” and that the “Power to learn from personal mistakes is profound."

Sergeant Smietana also answered questions and explained, in detail, the complex role of STEM in law enforcement. We appreciate your time and expertise!
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #Civics2020

post_text:
LET'S HEAR IT FOR COLGATE!
Sherburne-Earlville Elementary School students in grades 3-5 were loud and proud Wednesday morning, cheering on the Colgate Raider Nation women's #basketball team before, during and after its 72-53 win over Lafayette.

Our S-E kids sang the national anthem during Colgate's Kids Day pre-game festivities, which included a brief ceremony honoring senior guard Rachel Thompson for scoring 1,000 points at the college level.

We also enjoyed pizza for lunch, gave some love to Colgate's mascot, Raider, and stole the show at halftime with a mass jump-roping exhibition.

Sherburne-Earlville thanks Colgate University for giving back to local school districts and making its annual Kids Day one to remember!
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #RaiderNation #KidsDay2020

Junior Raven Rivenburgh’s fireplace theme (second photo) took second, followed by the lockers of sophomore Taylor Jennings, freshman Trinity Thornton and sophomore Abbigail Kochman.
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #HolidayLockers2019

post_text:
S-E SEEKING TYPIST!
The Sherburne-Earlville Central School District is accepting applications for a full-time TYPIST.

This entry-level, 12-month position at Sherburne-Earlville High School is a provisional appointment, dependent upon the results of Civil Service Typist Exam that will be given at a later date. Appointment may become permanent.

Salary is $11.80/hour or commensurate with experience.
Candidates should visit our employment page online at https://www.secsd.org/Employment.aspx for more information.

An employment application for Staff Positions must be completed and submitted to District Clerk, Sherburne-Earlville Central School, 15 School Street, Sherburne, NY 13460.

The deadline to apply is January 15, 2020.
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #Typist2020

post_text:
BEST DEAL IN TOWN!
The price was right for Sherburne-Earlville Elementary School students this past Thursday and Friday during our annual Holiday Bazaar!

Classes visited the makeshift gift shop in the west end of SEES during designated periods, giving kids a chance to purchase holiday presents for 50-cents apiece.

All of the new or gently-used items on sale at the Holiday Bazaar were donated by community members or purchased from an account that feeds the proceeds back into the program.

Former SEES secretary Maggie Fitzpatrick and former SECSD Superintendent Gayle Hellert spearheaded a crew of volunteers who made the Holiday Bazaar possible.

SEES accepts Holiday Bazaar items and monetary donations any time throughout the year. For more information on how you can help, call the main office at 607-674-7336.
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #HolidayBazaar2019

ADVENTURES IN KINDERGARTEN!
Sherburne-Earlville’s kindergarten kids were busy Friday morning with trips to Hi-Skor Lanes and our District Office.

Mrs. Claus welcomed all of our kindergarten classes for S-E’s annual visit to the Earlville, New York bowling alley. Check out some of the smiles at Hi-Skor Lanes, which continues to serve as the home of our high school #bowling teams.

Alison Kenyon’s class made its way back to the District Office today to decorate the tree next to the copier with homemade ornaments. And, in case you were wondering, the “seeds” from the North Pole last week grew into full-sized candy canes!
#WeAreSE #SEFamily #MaroonAndWhite #Kindergarten2019
